  "doc_id": "5350",
  "text": "The relationship between RNFL thickness and AL has been examined in several studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and has yielded conflicting results. Cheung et al [CITATION_3] reported that longer ALs were associated with thinner mean RNFL in a population-based study of Chinese adults. Knight el al 21 observed that AL had a negative correlation with the mean RNFL thickness, but a positive correlation with the temporal quadrant RNFL thickness in 63 Chinese adults. We found an association between the RNFL thickness and shorter AL, which has also been reported in previous investigations. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] AL and refraction are usually correlated, which could explain the association found in this study between the average RNFL thickness and hyperopic SE. A 1-mm axial elongation caused a mean 1.02µm RNFL thickness decrease, while a +1 dioptre increase (towards hyperopia) in refractive error caused a 0.62 µm increase in RNFL thickness, as a result of which, thinning of the RNFL with greater negative refraction (and longer AL) can be expected. The RNFL thinning is possibly due to the fact that there is a stretching of the eyeball in myopia, resulting in thinner RNFL in eyes with longer ALs. 28",
